{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17527331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17527331"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:30:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14205"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}},{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17583974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17583974"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:34:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:34:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14205"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14205","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14205"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.02,0.08,0.75,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6891"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102747"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6891","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6891"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14205"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85230"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"483"},{"type":"tags","id":"928"},{"type":"tags","id":"1804"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4986"},{"type":"tags","id":"4991"},{"type":"tags","id":"5351"},{"type":"tags","id":"11260"},{"type":"tags","id":"11622"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11645"},{"type":"tags","id":"11648"},{"type":"tags","id":"12734"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32927"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43504"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102747","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102747"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old Aboriginal woman presents to the General Practice clinic with worsening shortness of breath over the past two weeks. She has a medical history of chronic obstructive pulmonary disease (COPD) and type 2 diabetes. Her regular medications include salbutamol and metformin. She lives in a remote community with her extended family, including her children and grandchildren.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 92/min, blood pressure 138/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 37.2\u00b0C. Chest auscultation reveals diffuse wheezes and crackles.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter discussing her condition, you recommend she be admitted to the hospital for further management. The patient expresses hesitation about going to the hospital without consulting her family first.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Insist on immediate hospital admission due to her clinical condition","Discharge her with a prescription for oral antibiotics and steroids","Refer her to the Aboriginal Health Worker without further discussion","Offer to have a telehealth consultation with her family members","Provide written information and ask her to return tomorrow with her decision"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis scenario highlights the importance of cultural safety and respecting family dynamics when providing healthcare to Indigenous patients. The most appropriate next step is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eoffer to have a telehealth consultation with her family members\u003C/strong\u003E. This approach acknowledges the significance of family in the patient\u0027s decision-making process and demonstrates respect for her cultural values.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInsisting on immediate hospital admission\u003C/strong\u003E without considering the patient\u0027s wishes to consult her family first could be seen as culturally insensitive and may damage the therapeutic relationship. While the patient\u0027s clinical condition is concerning, it is not immediately life-threatening, allowing some time for family consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProviding written information and asking her to return tomorrow\u003C/strong\u003E with her decision does not adequately address the urgency of her condition or her desire to involve her family in the decision-making process. It may also present literacy challenges and does not actively facilitate family involvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDischarging her with a prescription for oral antibiotics and steroids\u003C/strong\u003E without addressing her concerns or involving her family in the decision-making process is inappropriate. It fails to provide the level of care her condition requires and disregards her expressed need for family consultation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReferring her to the Aboriginal Health Worker without further discussion\u003C/strong\u003E may be helpful as part of a comprehensive care plan, but it should not be the immediate next step. It doesn\u0027t address the urgent need for medical management or the patient\u0027s desire to consult with her family.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Indigenous healthcare, it\u0027s crucial to recognize that extended family members often play significant roles in healthcare decisions. By offering a telehealth consultation, the healthcare provider demonstrates flexibility and willingness to include the patient\u0027s family in the discussion about her care. This approach respects the patient\u0027s cultural values, promotes trust, and increases the likelihood of the patient accepting the recommended treatment plan.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cultural safety is crucial when providing healthcare to Indigenous patients, respecting their family dynamics and decision-making processes.","Extended family members often play significant roles in healthcare decisions for Indigenous patients.","Healthcare providers should be flexible and accommodating to include extended family in discussions about patient care when appropriate."],"references":["Australian Institute of Health and Welfare. (n.d.). Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Health Performance Framework: Tier 3\u2014Health system performance: Barriers to accessing health services. Australian Government. https://www.indigenoushpf.gov.au/measures/3-08-barriers-accessing-health-services"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85230"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14205"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85230"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-15T12:35:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-15T14:37:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6891"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102747"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"typ